{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DEXubA65tpUL76K4Z8F1hQ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have found the root cause! In `sendWatchCacheEvent` (line 892-893), when `!curObjPasses && oldObjPasses` (object no longer passes the filter, but previously did), the watch cache sends a DELETE event with `event.PrevObject.DeepCopyObject()`.\n\nThe problem is that `event.PrevObject` contains the **previous object** with its **own old resourceVersion** (the version of the object before the change, not the event's resourceVersion). The `watchCacheEvent.ResourceVersion` correctly reflects the event's resourceVersion, but the `PrevObject` is the old object stored in the watch cache with its own older resourceVersion.\n\n\nWhen a client-go informer receives this DELETE event and uses the object's resourceVersion to track the latest version, it sees the stale resourceVersion from the PrevObject instead of the current event's resourceVersion. Looking at how etcd3's watcher handles this, it decodes the old object but associates it with the current revision at the time of deletion, which is the correct approach here.\n\nThe etcd v2 watcher does something similar—it updates the old node's ModifiedIndex to match the deletion event's index before decoding, ensuring the old object carries the current event's resourceVersion. This pattern appears to be cut off mid-explanation...\n\nActually, I think I see the issue now. In the cacher's `sendWatchCacheEvent` method, when handling a DELETE event where the old object passes the filter but the current one doesn't, the PrevObject needs to have its resourceVersion bumped to match the event's resourceVersion, rather than keeping its stale version. the old object's resourceVersion, not the event's resourceVersion. So when the watch cache sends a DELETE event to a namespace-scoped watcher, it's including the previous object with its original resourceVersion (100), which causes the informer to incorrectly backtrack its tracked resourceVersion. Let me verify this is actually happening in the code... I need to make a copy of the PrevObject and update its resourceVersion to match the event's resourceVersion before sending it as a DELETE event, since the comment indicates we can't modify the original event. I'm also checking whether the watch.Deleted case has the same issue by looking at how curObjPasses is evaluated when the event type is Deleted.\n\nLooking at the logic, when an object moves out of filter scope during a MODIFIED event, it sends a DELETE with the old resourceVersion from PrevObject, which is the same bug. Let me search for the convertToWatchEvent function to see if similar issues exist elsewhere in the caching logic.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1249,"cache_read_input_tokens":52975,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1249},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1f1f0a74-24be-4718-b9fa-cd0683534a46","uuid":"c1ecf9d3-ebea-4a36-8347-1f51e99bde38"}
